      "id": 1,
      "text": "East Randolph earned its name from early settlers who came from Randolph, Vermont, and founded the community in 1826.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://historicpath.com/history/randolph"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "A station on the Atlantic & Great Western Railroad once connected East Randolph to major cities in the South and East.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://historicpath.com/history/randolph"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Lumber and metal works such as Gibb's Handle Factory (1874) and East Randolph Foundry (1873) drove the town’s 19th‑century economy.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4,
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://historicpath.com/history/randolph"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In 2010 voters dissolved the village, turning East Randolph into a hamlet—one of four county villages to do so that year.",
